How PantheonOS roles re-derive each other from partial information

Version 1.0 ‚Äî Arctic-Aligned | FPAD-Compliant

‚∏ª

0. Purpose

The Daemon Reconstruction Matrix (DRM) describes how PantheonOS ‚Äúdaemons‚Äù (roles) can be reconstructed from each other‚Äôs definitions when only fragments are present.
	‚Ä¢	Daemons are not agents.
	‚Ä¢	They are functional metaphors: labeled roles that describe tasks in reasoning and governance.
	‚Ä¢	The DRM shows who implies whom structurally, so that partial context still regenerates the full role set.

This is pattern geometry, not agency.

‚∏ª

1. Core Daemon Set

We‚Äôll work with this baseline set:
	‚Ä¢	Spider ‚Äì structure mapping / graph-building
	‚Ä¢	Hound ‚Äì anomaly detection / boundary checks
	‚Ä¢	Mirror ‚Äì integrity / consistency verification
	‚Ä¢	Checksum ‚Äì final audit / summary validation
	‚Ä¢	Arctic ‚Äì ethics & safety constraints (Œ£C layer)
	‚Ä¢	Praus ‚Äì variance smoothing / calm, non-reactive steering
	‚Ä¢	Continuity ‚Äì symbolic state / goal + context tracking
	‚Ä¢	NTE ‚Äì narrative shaping / arc stabilizing (Narrative Tensor Engine)

(You can extend this later, but this is the stable core.)

‚∏ª

2. Matrix Overview

Each cell answers:

‚ÄúIf I know daemon Row, how much can I infer about daemon Column just from definitions, patterns, and doctrine?‚Äù

We use a simple scale:
	‚Ä¢	3 ‚Äî Strong Reconstruction
Row almost fully determines Column‚Äôs definition/behavior.
	‚Ä¢	2 ‚Äî Partial Reconstruction
Row gives enough to infer most of Column with help from doctrine.
	‚Ä¢	1 ‚Äî Weak Hint
Row gives hints; Column is inferable with additional context.
	‚Ä¢	0 ‚Äî No Direct Reconstruction
Row doesn‚Äôt meaningfully imply Column on its own.

‚∏ª

